(13, '2015-06-03 22:41:53', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 12001, 'redistricted', 'Cape Breton-Canso', 'Nova Scotia', 'Barring unexpected circumstances, the incumbent should keep this riding.', 'Cape Breton-Canso covers a slightly wider geographical area now, as redistribution gave it a few Conservative voters from Central Nova. Liberal incumbent Rodger Cuzner is running for re-election, challenged by Conservative Adam Rodgers.  The other parties have not yet announced their candidates.', '', '', '', 12719, 17196, 7818, 1265, 0, 0, -4477, 4901, 38998, 26279, 67, 'Lib', 4477, 38998, 11.4801),
(14, '2015-06-04 01:46:52', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 12002, 'redistricted', 'Central Nova', 'Nova Scotia', 'Now an open seat', 'This is now an open race.  With Peter MacKay''s departure from the riding there is a big question as to whether this is truly a Conservative riding, or whether voters have been loyal to Peter MacKay and his father, Elmer MacKay.  With redistribution the Conservatives still have an edge, since the Conservative-leaning portion of Cumberland--Colchester--Musquodoboit Valley balances the NDP-leaning portion of Sackville--Eastern Shore that have been added to the riding.  Elmer MacKay was a Progressive Conservative who loaned his seat Brian Mulroney, who seems moderate and centrist compared to Stephen Harper.  Peter MacKay originally followed in the Progressive Conservative footsteps, but will go down in infamy for giving the Conservative name and brand to the Reform /Alliance Party, led by Stephen Harper.  Many voters have still voted their traditional preference, although the Conservative party dropped the "Progressive" out of its name and policies, and Brian Mulroney has spoken out strongly against many of the decisions made by the current Conservative Party.  David MacKay is running for the Liberals.  The NDP and Conservative parties do not yet have candidates.', '', '', '', 21494, 5424, 10422, 1479, 0, 57, 16070, 11072, 38876, 17325, 45, 'Tory', 11072, 38876, 28.4803),
