(205, '2015-06-03 20:12:43', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 48023, 'redistricted', 'Fort McMurray-Cold Lake', 'Alberta', 'The key to winning this riding is voter turnout.', 'Fort McMurray has usually had one of the lowest voter turnouts in the country, largely due to the number of newcomers in the riding and the long shifts the work demands.  The riding voted overwhelmingly Conservative in the 2011 General election, with fewer than 40% of eligible voters showing up.  The chart on this page shows the results of the 2014 by-election, a much closer race between Liberals and Conservatives, although only 15% of eligible voters cast ballots.  Much will depend on who shows up at the polls on October 19, and whether they see the recession in the Oil Patch as a problem the Conservatives are to blame for.  The riding is now Fort-McMurray-Cold Lake, and David Yurdiga, who won the by-election last year, is running for office again, challenged once again by Kyle Harrietha for the Liberals.  The NDP have not yet announced a candidate.', '', '', '', 5991, 4529, 1472, 453, 0, 351, 15733, 15134, 25552, 7051, 28, 'Tory', 15134, 25552, 59.2282),
