(217, '2015-06-04 14:26:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 59001, 'redistricted', 'Abbotsford', 'British Columbia', '', 'Voters in Abbotsford voted overwhelmingly for Conservative Ed Fast, Minister of International Trade, whose promises of jobs created by trade agreements <a href="http://canadians.org/blog/cetas-promise-80000-jobs-doesnt-add">has been shown to be just as imaginary</a> as the <a href="http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/ed-fast-pointy-finger/">gun he totes</a> in Parliament.  Jennifer Martel will run for the NDP.  The other parties have not yet chosen candidates.', '', '', '', 25060, 3260, 7209, 1744, 0, 196, 21800, 17851, 37469, 12213, 33, 'Tory', 17851, 37469, 47.6421),
(218, '2015-06-08 00:12:56', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 59002, 'new', 'Burnaby North-Seymour', 'British Columbia', 'High voter turnout needed to keep this riding from the Conservatives', 'Burnaby North-Seymour is a strange composition, made from the northern part of the old riding of Burnaby-Douglas and the eastern part of the old riding of North Vancouver.  The addition of Conservative-leaning voters from North Vancouver to the NDP-leaning voters of Burnaby gives a theoretical advantage to the Conservatives, if everyone were to vote exactly as they did in 2011 (illustrated by the graph here.)  The key to keeping this riding from the Conservatives is voter turnout.  In 2011 voter turnout in Burnaby was well below the national average, whereas voter turnout in North Vancouver waa quite high.  If more voters in Burnaby show up at the polls on October 19, the Conservative advantage on paper can easily be overcome.  Judge Carol Baird Ellan is running for the NDP, Mike Little for the Conservatives, Terry Beech for the Liberals and Lynne Quarmby for the Green Party.', '', '', '', 19150, 6804, 15219, 1679, 0, 437, 12346, 3931, 43289, 23702, 55, 'Tory', 3931, 43289, 9.08083),
(219, '2015-06-04 15:49:31', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 59003, 'redistricted', 'Burnaby South', 'British Columbia', 'A strong NDP incumbent', 'Burnaby South is made of the southern part of the former riding of Burnaby-Douglas and the western portion of Burnaby-New Westminster.  Kennedy Stewart, the NDP incumbent for Burnaby-Douglas, is running for re-election in this part of his old riding.  He has been a strong voice for the environment and for science during his time in office.  Adam Pankratz is running for the Liberals and Wyatt Tessari for the Green Party.  The Conservatives have not yet announced their candidate.', '', '', '', 14471, 4280, 16072, 1316, 0, 385, 10191, -1601, 36524, 21668, 59, 'NDP', 1601, 36524, 4.38342),
